## Bugs Fixed During Testing

### 1. [ApiError.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/utils/ApiError.js) — `errors` undefined (ReferenceError)
The constructor parameter was named `error` but the body referenced `errors`. Also fixed typo `succsess` → `success`.

```diff
- this.succsess = false;
- this.errors = errors;
+ this.success = false;
+ this.errors = error;
```

### 2. [user.model.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/models/user.model.js) — `next is not a function` in pre-save hooks
Mongoose 7+ async pre-save hooks should **not** accept `next`. The `next` callback pattern is for synchronous hooks only.

```diff
- userSchema.pre('save', async function (next) {
-   if (!this.isModified('passwordHash')) return next();
+ userSchema.pre('save', async function () {
+   if (!this.isModified('passwordHash')) return;
```

### 3. [index.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/index.js) — dotenv config path
The path was [./env](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/.env) instead of [./.env](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/.env), causing env vars to not load and MongoDB connection to fail.

### 4. Missing npm packages
`jsonwebtoken` and `bcryptjs` were imported but not in [package.json](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/package.json). Installed them.

### 5. [app.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/app.js) — Routes not mounted
Auth routes were never mounted. Added `app.use('/api/v1/auth', authRoutes)` and a global error handler.

### 6. [asyncHandler.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/utils/asyncHandler.js) filename typo
File was named [ayncHandler.js](file:///c:/Users/chall/OneDrive/Desktop/Ekyc/Backend/src/utils/ayncHandler.js) (missing 's'), causing `ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND`.

## ⚠️ Note on Test #11

After logout, the access token still works because the JWT is **stateless** — logout only clears the refresh token from the DB. The access token remains valid until it expires. This is standard JWT behavior but worth noting: if you need immediate token invalidation, you'd need a token blacklist/revocation strategy.
